\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.4}{\ignorespaces Spatial distribution of 16 sample points drawn in a two-dimensional parameter space, visualised at two grid resolutions. In (a) and (b), pure Monte Carlo sampling populates the space without structural constraint, producing irregular clusters and uncovered voids that persist regardless of grid resolution. In (g) and (h), the optimised Latin Hypercube Sampling stratification guarantee ensures that exactly one sample occupies each row and column of the partition grid, yielding substantially more uniform marginal coverage for the same number of evaluations \cite {deutschLatinHypercubeSampling2012}.}}{21}{}\protected@file@percent }
